(5) Simple modulo-based hash sharding (e.g., hash(key) % N shards) makes it easy to add or remove shards without significant data movement.

Simple modulo hashing requires massive data redistribution when changing shard count.
Going from hash(key) % 4 to hash(key) % 5 changes where most records map, requiring most data to move.
Consistent hashing is a different technique that minimizes this problem by only moving data from affected shards.

